{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hooloovoo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656872/1921010801/0046.xml":{"full_text":"Texas Will Ous\nNews Notes\nAmerican Legion Officials 1\nPaid for Land by Orient\nto Government in\nT1AIUJXGEN, Tex.. January 8.?\nFollowing a long conference with the\ntwo Japanese families which arrived\nat Harlingen to settle on Texas farm\nlands, American Legion representatives\ntoday laid plans for the return\nof the orientals to California. The\nlegion officials further pledged their\naid in the recovery of money paid by\nthe Japenese in the land deal which\nthe orientals declare invoiced a sum\nof $10,000.\nLegion attorneys advised the\n.tn.nanpse that an old Texas law.\npassed in 1892. forbids alien non-residents\nof the state to own land, and\nfurther informed them that escheat\nproceeding's will lie against Z.\nvamata of Los Angeles, from whom\nthe valley land was purchased. The\nnewcomers' farm implements remain\n;n cars at the railroad yards here. The\n>kuina brothers declared they knew\nnothing of the sentiment against\nthem here,,adding, \"We do not want\nto live where we are not wanted.\"\nCalifornia Senate Art*.\nSACRAMENTO. Calif., January 8.?\nThe California senate adopted yesterday,\n29 to 0, a resolution requesting\nrhe national government to agree to\nno treaty with Japan that would nullify\nthe state's anti-alien land law or\nthat would grant the right of citizenship\nto Japanese.\nThe resolution was taken up out of\norder with unanimous consent of the\nsenate so that quick action might be\nhad upon it.\n\"There are some phases of the negotiations\nthat cannot be discussed,\"\nsaid Senator Inman, who drew up the\nmeasure, \"but it can be said that there\nis danger, serious danger.' that the\nfederal government may give the\nright of citizenship to Japanese on\nthe Pacific coast as a sort of trading\nagreement. That would be unthinkable.\"\nThe resolution now goes to the\nassembly where final action is expected\nnext week.\nGu as Police WeifM.\nCLEVELAND, Ohio.?Toxic gas gre\"\"i\"\n\"\"H to nrevent the escape of\nprisoners during the world war have\nbeen suggested by American .Legion offlt\ni ials as a police weapon in Cleveland's\nfight against banditry and crime. The\nsuggestion that every police automobile\nh: equipped with these bombs was made\no Mayor W. S. Fitzgerald by Lieut. CoL\n>1. C. Goss of the legion.\ntampers in Mexico.\nLAREDO. Tex. ?Samuel Gompers.\npresident of the American Federation of\nLabor, left Nuevo Laredo, opposite here,\nlast night on a special car for Mexico\nCity, where he will attend the panAmerican\nlabor conference. Mr. Gompers\narrived here yesterday, and after\na busy day, during which he received\nmany guests, crossed the border at 5\no'clock.\nAnnounce \"\"Open Shop.\"\nRALEIGH, N. C.?In an advertisement\nappearing In a local newspaper\nThirteen leading building contractors,\nincluding electrical, painting and roofing\nconcerns, announced that on and\nafter March S they would adopt the\n\"open shop\" system in employing workmen.\n1\nAgree en Shipping.\nHAMBURG.?Representatives of the\nUarelmafk nklnniw. {ninneetn etui etffi. I\nrials of file Hamburg-American line\ndiscussed the allotment of sailing routes\nand distribution of freights at a conference.\nMutually satisfactory agreements\nwere reached, says a statement Issued\nby representatives of the combined interests\nafter the meeting. The assignment\nof docks for the American ships\nalso was definitely fixed. CoL Ryan of\nthe Harriman lines took part in the\nconference.\nPay Ball Padding Charged.\nDETROIT, Mid*.?A scheme for pad- 1\nding city pay rolls that, it is charged.\nhas covered a period of several\nmonths, -was disclosed, according to\nthe police. In the arrest of Albert\nCrstadt, a timekeeper In one of the\ndepartment of' public works yards.\nUrstadt, according to the police, has\nconfessed and implicated several other\nemployes. The amount of the defalcations\nhas not been determined.\nEthel Barrynaore Bads Dates.\nCINCINNATI, Ohio.?Miss Ethel\nRarrymore. actress, who is snffering\nfrom rheumatism, has canceled her\nremaining engagements in this city.\nShe may be compelled to remain in\nCincinnati several weeks, her shysi\nians said.\nUwwHiww Mhf\nLiAEDO, Tex.?Two alleged liquor\nsmugglers were killed in a fight with\nTexas rangers In Zapata county, sixty\nmiles east of Laredo, according to advices\nreceived bore. Several escaped.\nNone of the rangers was injured. Sevral\npack horses were killed in the exchange\nof shots. A quantity of liquor\nwas found in the packs the animals\nwere- carrying.\nPrayer Factor, Saya Ward lag.\nBRIDGEPORT, Conn.?\"Prayer is a\ndominant factor for a successful life,\"\nwrote President-elect Harding to the\nRev. Benjamin Root, rector of St.\nPaul's Episcopal ChuTch, in a letter\njust received. The question had been\nasked of Mr. Harding as to what he\nconsidered constituted \"success.\"\nRattle Aaafveraary Observed.\nNEW ORLEANS.?The anniversary\nof the battle of New Orleans was ob'\nserved here today with the customary\nexercises at Chalmette battlefield. The\nanniversary being a legal holiday,\nbanks and publics offices were closed.\nDarkaa'i Soa to Marry.\niJONDON.?Announcement is made of\nthe engagement of Terry C. Durham, a\nlieutenant in the United States artillery\nand son of W. A. Durham of Appomattox.\nVa_ to Mary, daughter of\nSir Leicester Harmsworth. brother of\nJ>ord Northcliife.\nPreacher Dies' Suddenly.\nVALDOSTA. Ga.?The Rev. R. P.\nPain of Hahira. well known minister\nm tho South Georgia Methodist conference,\nwho was a victim of suspended\nanimation during a meeting\nof ministers at Hahira Wednesday.\nwhen for more than fifteen minutes\nhe was believed to be dead, died white\nreturning from the station, where he\nwent to bid farewell to departing\npreachers.\nNtulNt Gets Library.\nSTANFORD UNIVERSITY. CaJif.?\nProf. Paul Miliukov, Russian secretary\nof foreign affairs, after the revolution\nor 1*17, has presented to Stanford\nUniversity his private library on\nKnaslaii history, said to be one of the\nmoat comprehensive collections in exatenee.\nit is announced.\nA sale Is Cera King.\nI4AFAYETTE. lnd. William H.\nBaker, whose home is near Lyons, in\nSreene county, is the 1920 Indiana\norn king. He raised an average of\nI2S.8 bushels an acre in the annual\nfive-acre production contest held under\nthe auspices of Purdue University.\naccording 16 an announcement\n1 T.ade at the university. Mr. Baker\n*1mo was corn king in 1319, producing\nan average of 121 bushels an acre.\nTe Operate sa Ueldea Rale Plaa.\nCHATTANOOGA. Tenn.?The Civl\nan Businessman Club of Chattanooga\ndetermined to apply for the inoor\nooration of a new industry to operate\nonder the principles of the golden\nrule, as enunciated by Christ in His\nsermon on the mount. The club dr'\nMed to apply for a J.IO.OOO charter for\nthe \"A. Nash Company of Tennessee.\"\nA. P. Crarkett Keaad Dead.\nBRISTOL Vs.?A. P. Crockett, lawyer,\nformerly private recretary to\nt Japanese;\nFrom Over V. S.\n*romise Recovery of Money\nlals?California Appeals\ni Anti-Alien Case.\nRepresentative* C. Bascomb Slemi\nwas found dead in his office at Coe\nbum, Va. Heart failure was th(\ncause of his death.\nFarmer-Labor Body to Meet.\nCLEVELAND. Ohio.?The annua\nconvention of the Farmer-Labor Co\noperative congress will meet in cieve\nland for a three-day session, begin\nning February 10, Warren S. Stone\ngrand chief of the Brotherhood o\nLocomotive Engineers, announced today.\nRepresentative^ of progressiv<\nfarm organizations representing ovei\n900,000 farmers, delegates of varioui\nlabor organizations and of scvera\nhundred co-operative societies wili\nattend.\nGeorge Crow Dies at 10S.\nWHEELING. W. Va.?George Crow,\nwho was rejected because of his advanced\naged by a recruiting officer\nwhen he sought to enlist for military\nservice in the civil war, is dead at\nthe family home, Denver Hill, near\nLittleton, W. Va. Mr. Crow recently\ncelebrated his lOSth birthday anniversary\nby riding eight miles on his horse\nto the home of one of his sons.\n\"Birth Control\" Conspiracy Charge.\nSAN FRANCISCO. Indictments\ncharging a conspiracy to use the\nmails to defraud in connection with\nthe alleged distribution of birth control\nliterature among woman students\nof the University of California\nwere returned by the federal grand\njury yesterday against Dr. Waldo\nRichardson of Fair Oaks, Sacramento\ncounty, and his wife, Mrs. O. B. Richardson.\nFederal officials said the\nRichardsons, who were arrested once\nbefore in connection with the alleged\ndistribution of similar literature,\nwere agents of a Kansas City concern.\nFour Women Elected to Office.\nRICHMOND,* W. Va.?Four woman\ncandidates for municipal offices in yesterday's\nelections here and at Sutton\nwere elected, returns tabulated today\nshowed. Mrs. Agnes Duffy and Mrs. C.\nB. Wright, both democrats, were elected\nmembers of the Richwood city council.\nMrs. Kate B. Frame was elected\nto the Sutton council^ while Mrs. B. P.\nHall was named school commissioner.\nWest Point Cadet Found Dead.\nWEST POINT. N. Y.?Dennis Totten\nof MDford, COnn., nineteen-year-old\ncadet at the military academy here, was\nfound dead on the reservation at 9\no'clock yesterday. A board of officers\nis investigating the cause of death.\nOfficials said that Totten,. who was a\nthird-year man, had not been in good\nhealth recently.\nSick Man Stirs Oat of Jail.\nCLARKSBURG. W. Va.?Ill of pneumonia,\nArnold Smith of West Union\nmade a daring escape from the Harrison\ncounty jail here today. He sawed\nin two the heavy iron bars 'protecting\nthe window in his hospital room on the\nthird floor of the jail. Tbe police believe\nthat if he succeeded in making\nhis way into the bills be would die before\nhe could be recantiireri\nThreat hy \"Outlaw\" R. R. Men.\nTOLEDO, Ohio.?Aroused over -what\nthey claim are attempts made in Toledo\nby \"outlaw\" railroad organisations to\ndisrupt the old railroad brotherhoods,\nofficials of the last-named organizations\ndeclared that they are about to face a\ngreater onslaught than that of last June\nwhen the Chicago yardmen's association\ncaused walkouts all over the country.\nTo cope with the situation a meeting\nof the executive committee of the local\nbrotherhoods has, been called for tomorrows\nAlleged Counterfeiting Outdt.\nMACON, Ga.?Secret service .agent*,\nfollowing a clue from Atlanta, raided a\nroom in a leading hotel here, seizing\nwhat they allege to be a complete counterfeiting\noutfit and material alleged to\nbe used by \"confidence\" men. An electrical\nprinting press, paper similar to\nthat used for money, ink and rubber\nstamps were in the room.\nThreaten Death; Bssntk Home.\nROANOKE, Va.?Under threats of\ndeath, two unknown white men drove\nMrs. Walter Leffel and her two children\nfrom their home twelve miles east of\nTazewell, Va.. and then ransacked the\nhouse, securing a small sum of money.\nSheriff Harman, with the assistance of\nbloodhounds, tracked the men to the\npublic highway, where it is believed\nthey used an automobile to escape.\nShip Company Receivers,\nnisw tukk.?Receivers for the Downey\nShipbuilding Corporation of New\nYork were appointed in the federal court\nhere and in Wilmington, Del. The company,\nwhich was organized in 1917, has\na plant at Staten Island, covering 165\nacres.\nLargest PeasaeoU Catefc.\nPEN8AOOLA, Fla.?The fishing smack\nYakima, Capt. Gustavus Hansen, pf the\nK. E. Saunders Co. fleet, reported in\nwith till*largest catch ever made by a\nvessel out of this port. The Yakima\nbrought in 43,000 pounds of red snappers\nand 3.000 pounds of groupers, after being\nout twenty-three days. Ten men\ncomprised the crew and each fisherman's\nshare for making the catch was\n*167.15.'\nBays Sarplas Aircraft.\nNEW YORK.?Announcement was\nmade here that the Aero-Marine Plane\nand Motor Company' had taken over\n*4.000,000 worth of surplus naval aircraft\nand engines. Included in the lot are\n125 HS-2 flying boats, used during the\nwar ior coast parrot wont, wnicn will be\nreconstructed into passenger craft.\n300 Saved to Hospital Fire.\nMIULEDGKVILA.E. Ga.?Nearly 300\npatients, among whom were 75 shellshocked\nsoldiers from the world war,\nwere carried from the turning buildings\nwhen fire partially destroyed the\nAllen Invalid Home yesterday afternoon.\nThe institution is noted\nthroughout the south for the treatment\nof nervous and mental dlseaaea\nNot a life was lost. The property loss\nwill exceed $100,000.\nIndictments to Slaying.\nATHENS, Ala.?Developments In\nthe investigation of the murder of\nJohn King, Limestone county farmer,\nwhich occurred near 8tewarts cross\nroads last December, came rapidly yesterday.\nwhen the grand jury returned\nindictments against a white man and\ntwo negroes, charging murder. When\nthe cases of Adz Jones and George\nPorter, previously Indicted for the\nmurder, were called In circuit court\nyesterday morning, at the/earnest solicitation\nof their attorneys. ~a continuance\nuntil the March term of court was\ngranted.\nVirginia Rand Project*.\nROANOKE, Va.?Two hundred men,\nrepresenting seven southwest Virginia\ncounties, met at St. Paul and\norganized the CI inch-Cum her land\nGood Roads Association, farmer Gov.\nH. C. Stuart presided. John W. C.\nPaulkley of Bier Stone Gap was elected\npresident of the new association,\nwhich will boost several important\nroad projects. t\nHas Mertt Bads' Heeord.\nMOBILE, Ala.?Marshall Oliver, a\nMobile boy, holds the nation's record\nin the number of Boy Scouts merit\nbadges lie has won, it was announced\nby J. E. Meredith, executive of th?\nMobile scout council. This Mobile\nyouth lias sixty of the badges to hit\ncredit.\nWill Return Stolen Whisky.\nNEW ORLEANS.?A large quantity\nof whisky, wines and cordials, captured\nby the police when they raidec\ntile home of a man alleged to hav<\nbeen implicated in numerous burglaries\nhere during the past tw<\nmonths, will be turned ver to th<\nowners without question and then\nwill be no Volstead act proceedings\n.District Attorney Henry Mooney announced,\n\nMUTT AND JEFF?\n[me bos* was fooush^\\\n7b 6?ve JCFF a 46ft\nth stabl? 1 th? r\\i?t j\nwas b\\)e at thg j\nf track am Hour\nA6o UUlTH IHPtTy\nHoftsc? y\nDM HOUSE\nIN BADMDI1N\nInmates Sleep Four to a Bed\nUnder Leaky Roof,\nOwen Says.\nImmediate steps Trill be taken by\nthe public safety group of the City\nClub to induce Congress to grant the\nappropriation asked by the house of\ndetention for its maintenance. Startling\ndisclosures of the condition and\nequipment of the institution, which\nhas been only recently moved into the\nold Emergertcy Hospital, were made\nlast night at a meeting of the group\nby Claude W. Owen, who has made an\nextensive investigation with members\nof his committee.\nA committee, consisting of Mr. Owen\nas chairman. Dr. Charles W. Cuthbertson\nand E. J. Febrey. was appointed\nto visit leading members of\nthe Senate District committee on\nMonday and urge restoration of the\ndesired appropriation of $38,240, which\nwas cut by the House down to $27,000.\nHere are .some of the conditions revealed\nby Mr. Owen in his report:\nAll of the beds are of the sinerle\ntype and frequently two. three and\nfour persons have to sleep in the\nsame bed. The springs sag so much\nthat they almost touch the floor, and\njust a few months ago there was exactly\none-half a blanket for each bed.\nGirls Have Two Mirrors.\nThe roof leaks, and when it rains\nthe inmates have to set buckets\naround .to catch the drip.\nThe dozen and more girl and woman\ninmates always at the Institution\nhave to light for two mirrors. There\nis not a single chair in the boys'.department.\nThere were once twelve\nwhole chairs in the dining room, but\nas the number of inmates is nearly\nhi ways more than twice tljis number,\nthe chairs have just naturally broken\ndown.\nTwo clerks work ten to twenty-four\nhours a day, tend furnace on the side\nand are offered the munificent salary\nof $1,000 a year each.\nA supervisor, who is supposed to be\na professional \"mother\" to all of the\ninmates and works, about sixteen\nhours a day. Is offered $1,200 a year.\nA cook, whose \"family\" varies from\nten to forty a .day, is offered $500 a\nyear, arid ahe has to teach the girl Inmates\ncooking en the side.\n\"These conditions are apalllng,\" egid\nMr. Owen. \"When .the institution was\nmoved to its present site, the old\nEmergency Hospital building, $18,000\nwas appropriated for renovating the\nbuilding, but not'a cent was given for\nequipment.\nSome Private Ceatrffeatieaa.\n\"The needs are so pressing that it\nhas been necessary to seek private\ncontributions to carry on the work.\nIt is a shame that the Commissioners\nhave to get down on their knees to\nget Congress to appropriate a paltry\nsum.\"\n\"While these inmates are suffering\nfrom lack of equipment,\" said Mr.\nFebrey, \"surplus supplies belonging\nto the government are going to rot and\n1 ruin in East Potomac Park. The genI\neral supply committee and the War\nnpnartmant hMIl llll? BMnnllM of\noots, matressesi sheets a<id blankets.\nTet governmental red tape prevents\nthe District from using these supplies.\n\"It an emphasizes the need of national\nrepresentation for the District.\nIf we had our representatives on the\nhill we would get some consideration.\"\nMANY WOMEN KEEP\nPLACES TAKEN IN WAR\nDirector of Bureau Be porta Only\nPart of Those Have Lost Jobs\nBecause of Be turning Ken.\nCHICAGO, January 8.?Only part of\nthe women engaged in industry during\nthe war period have lost their places\nthrough the return of men from the\nwar and lack of employment. Hiss Mary\nAnderson, director of the women's bureau\nof tbe United States Department:\nof Labor, reports.\n\"Statements to the bureau from hun-\ndreds of Industry heads who employed\nonly women during the war show they\nhave retained their female help, while\nothers state they have replaced their\nwomen with male workers,\" Miss Anderson\nsaid.\n\"Because of the volume of unemployment\nthroughout the country today no\naccurate figures as to the number of\nwomen employed in industries at present\nas compared with the war period\nare obtainable.\nVI believe that when figures of the\n1920 census are available, they will\nshow more than 12,000,000 women in\ngainful occupation. The census, however,\nwill not set forth the present\nsituation because unemployment has\nincreased by leaps and bounds since\nit was taken.\n\"Women won the admiration of employers\nduring the war period by their\nability to fill in on men's Jobs. Take,\nfor Instance, lathe operators. Thousands\nof women became very efficient\nand stUl retain their places beside men\noperators. The war gave American\nwomen a new opportunity in industry\nana uiey graspea n.\"\nThere are two factors needed to insure\nwomen their place in industry.\nMiss Anderson said. Protective legislation\ntor the eight-hour day is badly\nneeded, she declared, and lidded that\nthe women must \"organise within the\nnext few years.\"\nWith the return of prosperity, in;\nd us tries will clamor for woman workI\nera, in the opinion of Miss Mary E.\nMcDowell of the University of Chicago\n1 Settlement House, who is chairman of\nthe women in industry committee of\nthe National League of Woman Voters.\nBILL TO AID GERMANS.\nSenator King, democrat, Utah, com\npleted yesterday a Mil proposing to reI\nstore to German cltisene all property\ns taken over by the alien property cua\ntodian during the war. He plans to\nintroduce it Monday. A special court\ns for the consideration of the claims\ns would be created by the measure, and\nthe United States would not have to\npay more than the $709,000,000 realized\nfrom- the-property,\nAnd When the Horse 1\nA (l AlfTT\nII> A, JCFF, I I\nVWHV DoWT f MU\nClaims Blue Laws\nOf South Dakota\nAdmit of Evasion\nPIERRE, S. I).. January 8.?\nSouth Dakota'* blur law* must\neither be repealed or amended\nno they,may be enforced. In the\nopinion of Attorney General\nPayne, who declare* the wordIns\nof present statute* leads to\nevasion of the law's intent.\n\"Gainful occupations\" are\nprohibited In South Dakota on\nSundays, but no section of the\nstatute# deflnc* Just what are\n\"gainful occupations.\"\nTherefore, -base ball, motion\npicture*, dancing, theaters,\nboxing and various other thins*\nthat, it 1* declared, the law was\ndesigned to prohibit on Sundays,\nare made legal by lack\nof specification, according to\nthe attorney general.\nProponent* of a \"blue Sunday\"\nIn thin state are eager to\nhave the legislature at it* rotating\nsession amend the blue\nlaws and enlarge their scope\nso that they may speclgeally\ncover all forms 'of amusement\nand commerce not \"absolutely\nessential.\"\ntin the' other hand, sentiment\nappears to be developing In\nfavor of the repeal of all blue\nlaw*. Backers* of this proposition\nurge among their argument*\nthat the prohibition of\nSunday base ball would mean\ndeath of the South Dakota\nLeague.\n4 1\nSAYS U. S. WILL NEVER\nBECOME 'LITERALLY DRY'\nCommissioner Kramer, However,\nDeclares the Prohibition LawIs\n\"Here ta Stay.\"\nThe United States will never be literally\ndry prohibition, Commissionei\nKramer declared in a statement yesterday,\nthough he expressed tbe opinion\nprohibition^ is here to stay. Sentiment\nthroughout the country, he said, if\ncontinually growing stronger tor prohibition,\nand practical prohibition\nwill come after the present generation,\nwhich is familiar with liquor, if\ngone, he continued, though there probably\nalways will be some few individuals\nwho will make intoxicants in\ntbeir homes. The sons and daughter!\nof the men of today, he asserted, will\ngrow up without a taste for liquor.\nThe commissioner declared that\ndespite evidence of lawbreaking in\nsome sections, the country as a\nwhole is behind the amendment to the\nConstitution. New York and the east,\nho asserted, cannot be considered at\nreflecting the attitude of the eountrj\nat large, and in general west of Pittsburgh\nthe country is dry.\nDifficulties experienced with prohibition\nagents were to be expected\nhe declared, but as a body they serf\ndoing their duty. Most of the enforce\nment agents Mr. Kramer described ai\nmen who could \"take a drink in ordei\nto carry out their orders,\" but his\nbest agent, he said, was a Methodisl\nminister.\nFederal prohibition directors ir\neach state have been asked by Commissioner\nKramer to keep a card index\nof-all persons Imving permits tc\npurchase liquor, so that a closer supervision\ncan be kept of such traffic\nData- on the cards will show the\namount of liquor in possession ol\neach license holder, the amount and\nkind of liquor bought, the amount\nshipped and delivered and the name\nof the person using the permit.\nRAILROAD HEADS FAVOR\nMEETING LABOR DIRECT\n\nBelieve Differences Can Be Adjusted\nEasier This Way Than\nby V. 8. Board.\nNKW YORK, January 8.?Adjustment\nof differences between the country's\nrailroads and their labor is a\nproblem that can be taken up mo?\nsatisfactorily by individual railroads\nand their employes than by the United\nStates labor board.\nThis was the decision of executives\nof approximately one hundred railroads,\nmeeting here, who discusset\ntransportation subjects, among their\npassage of a bill providing that th<\nSecretary of the Treasury make partial\npayments to the roads in settlement\nof the government's guarantees\nby the present Congress. It was decided\nto urge Alfred P. Thom, general\ncounsel to the executives, to do everything\npossible to have such a measure\ncarried through. These settlements\nit was said, involve about (400,000,000.\nU. S. COST CUT INHALF.\nTreasury Reports 1920 Reduction\nin Government Expenses.\nReduction of more than 50 per cen\nin the cost of running the federal gov\nernment during 1920, compared with thi\nexpenditures in 1919. is shown in th<\nlast Treasury statement.\nOrdinary disbursements have not ye\nbeen reduced to the 14,000.000,000 a yea\nmark set by Secretary Houston, as tto\namount thgt would be needed for eacl\nof the five succeeding years, but the re\nduction is rapidly approaching that fig\nure. The expenditures outside of pay\nments on the public debt last year ap\nproxlmated $5,064,000,000, compare\nwith $11,728,000,000 for the year pre\nvious.\n\nHCX TWO VICE CHAIRMEN.\nCharles T. Clagett and Charles W\nRag have been chosen by Mai. Harr;\nL. Gessford to serve as vice chair\nmen of the committee on public order\nChairman Gessford's selections havt\nbeen approved by the inaugural com\nmittee. It is probable that announce\nmerib of the full committee will bi\nmade next week.\nThe committee will be composed o\nabout 500 representative business ant\nprofessional men, and subcommittee\nwill be appointed .as soon as tmpor\ntant details of the racgural are com\nHeted,\nfawns, Jeff Slips the Bit\nDewey Shaft\nCondensed Net\nU. S. to Be Asked to Approf\nfor Monument?Trah\nAid at B\nBy 10.' Associated frese.\nMANILA, P. i? January 8.?The\nDewey memorial committee today decided\nupon the erection of a statue to\ncost 8200,000 as a monument to Admiral\nDewey on the shore of Manila bay.\nThe United States Congress will be asked\nto appropriate half the funds and the\nPhilippine legislature to appropriate\nhalf.\nAsk Withdrawal of Quest loa.\nBERN.?The Swiss federal council has\nwritten to the executive council of the\ninternational labor bureau at Geneva\nproposing that questions relating to\nagricultural labor be withdrawn from\nthe agents of the international labor\nconfesence, which-is to meet at Geneva\nin the spring.\nPrisoner Was \"Footless.\"\nMONTREAL..?Because the police appropriated\nhis sole pair of trousers on\nthe ground that they bore important\nmarks of evidence, Albert Lonahan appeared\nin court \"pantless\" in connection\nwith a charge of appropriating $10,000\nworth of negotiable securities from the\nAmerican Plumbing Supplies, Limited,\non Christmas day. For modesty's sake\nthe court loaned him an overcoat, the\nfirst covering for his nether limbs in the\nlast two weeks. i\nGet Train of Red Cross Aid.\nBUDAPEST.?A train of thirty-one\ncarloads of American Red Cross supplies,\nvalued at $100,000. has arrived\nhere from Paris for distribution among\nJ ..kilrloon\ntne nospiuus aim ucomuio viumi^m.\nWool yarn will be given to 25.000 school\nteachers to make their own garments\npreparatory to the reopening of the\nschools, which now are closed owing to\nthe lack of fuel.\nNew Mexican Oil Find. 1\nMEXICO CITY.?Petroleum has been\ndiscovered at San Andres, Tuxtla, fifty\nmiles south of the port of Vera Cruz,\n1 according to advices from that region.\nwhich say that preparations are being i\nmade for extensive development of the\nfield. This is the first indication of pe- j\ntroleum in that section. I\nWill Boyeett Spate's Goods.\nJ BARCELONA. Spain.?All revolutionary\norganizations of the world\nare required to start on January 16\nmaterials coming from Spain, in a\nucts and to refuse to load and unload\nSpanish merchandise, or work with\nmaterials coming from Spain in a\nI manifesto iss-ued by Syndicalist General\nConfederation of Labor. Among\nthe organizations to which the manii\nfesto has been sent are the Industrial\nl Workers of the World, New York;\ni the General Workers' Federation,\nBuenos Aires, and Russian, German,\ni Portuguese, Dutch, French, Italian\nand English societies,\nMea in Bnrnlng Mine.\nMADRID.?Twenty three coal miners\n,,were imprisoned in the lower galleries\nof a pit in the Lo Carolina coal fields;\nwhich are afire, says a message from\ni the governor of Jaen province. He\nfears all the men will be lost as the\ni pit is not equipped with adequate Ore\napparatus. An explosion is said to\nhave occurred in the pit on Thursday\ni when forty-five men were below.\nTwenty-two of them escaped, and ex.\nperts believe some of the others were\novercome by gas.\n000 Qaake Deaths.'\nI PARIS.?Dispatches to the Albanian\nauthorities indicate that the recent\ni earthouake disaster in the Elbassan\ndistrict was far more serious than was\nshown by earlier reports. The shocks\nwere especially heavy in the area between\nTepelini and Elbassan. The\nlatter city was almost completely\nrazed. Near Tepelini. which is about\nfifty miles south of Elbasa&n, mountains\ncrumbled away. Six hundred\npersons are said to have been killed,\nfifteen villages were destroyed and\n30.000 persons have been made homeless.\n\nDeath by Natural Causes.\nLONDON.?A verdict of death due\nto natural causes was recorded by the\ncoroner at an Inquest over the body\nof Elmer J. Pelt of Tacoma,\" Wash,\nwho died at a prominent hotel in\ni London.\ni Japanese Cadets Are Guests.\nSANTIAGO, Chile.?A contingent of\n700 naval cadets and sailors of the\nJapanese cruisers Asama and Iwate.\nwhich now are at Valparaiso, visitedI\nI'ha mlnlolAp nf war tAti. i\nklllO UVJi \"V w?. wu\ndered a banquet to the officers of the\ncruisers.\nDeputies Create Mialstry.\nSANTIAGO, Chile.?The chamber of\ndeputies has adopted a bill providing\nfor the creation of a ministry of agriculture\nand labor. The bill was recommended\nin the ministerial program\nof the new government of President\nAleenandri.\nWill Ask as te Sentences.\nBUDAPEST.?Michael Junghert of\nt MHi SS\nl. II\n;i /zorc/c just\nt and without\nInstant\nthe table dr\nprefer tote\nbecause of r\nftara; model\neuperiorhe*\n?a;\nr\nK\nin His Mouth. (0wri|\nuuTrweif* /yuetx/nVe^\ncfwrr tAyce Ww*. H1 GeT -auVl\nT tiu t. cte^)||| V /vmt> cte/\nHIS Hocfrs. t mew!\n\"^W0^I f Vo\nx I\nfor Manila; j\nws From Abroad j\nmate Half of $200,000 Cost\nn Load of Red Cross\nI\nudapest.\nthe foreign office will go to Keval,\nEsthonia, next week to negotiate with\nMaxim l#itvinofr. assistant Russian\nsoviet commissary of foreign affairs,\nregarding the former peoples' commissaries\nsentenced to death in Budapest\nrecently, as the Moscow government\nhas threatened reprisals if the\nmen are executed.\nPogrom Victim* Would Come.\n\"WARSAW.?The minister of the interior\nhas requested the foreign office\nto endeavor to obtain the admission\nof Ukrainian pogrom victims into the\nUnited States. The request was made\nas a result of the efforts of local\nJewish, leaders.\nAlberta Wheat Ooes by Canal.\nCALGARY.?The first important\nshipment of Alberta, wheat to Europe\nby way of the Pacific and the Panama\ncanal is now en route to Liverpool\nand French ports from Vancouver, it\nwas learned today. The steamship is\ncarrying 3,000 tons.\nFire in Guatemala City.\nSAN SALVADOR.?Fire seriously\ndamaged the city hall in Guatemala\nCity, the civil registrar's office and\nthe municipal library, being in the\nsection of the building where the\nflames originated. Many of the records\nand contents of the library were\nsaved from the fire, which, it is indicated,\nwas of incendiary origin.\ni\nEditor Given British Honor.\nSAN SALVADOR.?Miguel Pinto, director\nof the newspaper Mario Latino\nof this city, was today decorated with\nthe insignia of the most excellent order\nof the British empire, which was\nawarded him by King George as a\ntoken of thanks for his work in support\nof the allied cause during the\nworld war.\nWOULD PROCEED WITH\nNAVY BUILDING PROGRAM\nBepresentative Britten's Bill Discourages\nCutting Strength\nThrough Foreign Agreements.\nOpposing all plans for cutting down\nthe nation's naval strength through\ndisarmament agreements with foreign\ncountries, Representative Britten\nof Illinois, republican member of\nthe House naval affairs committee,\nhas introduced a joint resolution to\ndirect the Navy Department to proceed\"\nat once with its big building\nprogram.\nComing on the heels of the naval\nreduction movement in the Senate,\nthe Britten resolution was designed\nby its author to put squarely before\nCongress the question whether this\ncountry should endeavor to join with\nGreat Britain and Japan in a \"naval\nholiday\" or go ahead with the construction\nof ships.\nThe resolution declares \"that the\nUnited States is unwilling to commit\nits economic and political independence\nto the fetters of an international\ntreaty materially limiting naval armaments,\nthereby-involving its freedom\nof action in ways and for objects not\nat present discernible, and that all\nwarship construction authorized to\ndate be completed in the shortest\npracticable time commensurate with\nthe nation's desire for economy and\nsound business Dractice in the private\nand trovernment shipbuilding: yards.\"\nMr. \"Britten declared, in a statement,\nthat there was no human way for the\nBritish navy to retain the supremacy\nof the sea without this so-called\n\"naval holiday,\" and that there could\nbe no half-way house between entire\ntrust and no armament on the one\nhand, \"and distrust with such armament\nas we think desirable on the\nother.\"\nWALL1S OUT OF ARMY.\nFirst to Present Wounds in Wax\nand Paint.\nCapt. J. P. Wallis of the Army Medical\nMuseum, credited with founding:\nthe first American school in the important\nart of presenting: diseases and\nwounds in wax and paint, has been\ndischarged from the Array and returned\nto civil life, it was announced\ntoday.\nMustard burns and gas poisoning\nare shown In Capt Wallis' wax models\nwith realism.\nThe models show gaping shrapnel\nand bullet wounds.\nThe value to the War Department\nof Capt Wallis' work has won him\ncommendation upon more than one occasion,\nand his retirement from the\ngovernment service was accompanied\ntoday by expressions of regret from\nh i ch nfficl <a In\n9 j\ni llMP\nsntly\ni bet of waste\nPOSTUM\nIrtkso many\na or coffee\nich uniform\na&ecostand\nAh value.\n\nsrHnarr. ?i\n;ht, 1821, by H. 0. lisbcr. Trade mark\nresistered V. 8. Fat. Off.)\nill i i f i .1.\n{I'M WAITIMG Xr\nf -I fOtfc HIM Tb\nV* i U6 DeuiN %o.\ny\nWireless to Carry j\nSermon and Music j\nIn800-MileRadius\nPITTSBURGH, January S.?\nPersona rraMlnic within SOO\nalien of Pittsburgh, aa< hay-\nlac; wlrelena telephone reeelv- 1\nera, will be able to \"listen in*'\non aerrlcea' at the Calvary\nProtentant Kplscopal Church\nhere tomorrow. A mannfaeturlair\nconcern, handling radio\ntelephone equipment, baa laatuiled\ntransmitting apparatus\nat the church.\nThe company han been ?dvtaed\nby many amateur operator*\nthat they enjoyed the\nmuaie and aermon delivered at\nx the ehnreh laat Sunday, and\ntransmitted on the wireless\ntelephone.\nAmong those who \"listened\nIn\" last weelt were operators\nat Bandett, Minn.; Kllendalr, S,\nD; Merchantville, X. J.s SpringHeld,\nMass., and many other\npoints.\nCOSTLY FEDERAL PLANT I\nSOON WILL BE AT WORK\nFinishing' Touches Being Put on\nHelium Gas Establishment\nat Fort Worth.\nFORT WORTH, Tex., January 8.?\nFinishing touches are being put on the\nfederal government's $6,000,000 helium\ngas plant, six miles north of Fort\nWorth, and operations on a large scale\nare expected to begin soon. This announcement\nis made by Lieut. Griffin,\nwho is in charge, as the representative\nof the Nevy Department. The last of\nthe machinery was shipped to Fort\nWorth before the first of the year.\nEstablished yln 1917 at a cost of\n$800,000. the plant has been an expert-\nment station thus far. But the worth\nof the gas and its economy for use by\nthe Navy and Army balloons have been\nproved to the satisfaction of military\nexperts.\nIn addition to the plant near Fort\nWorth, the government also has con-\nstructed a private pipe line from Petro\nlia, which brings natural gas from\nthe Lone Star Comnany's wells right 1\ninto the plant. After the argon qualities,\nfrom which helium is obtained,\nhave been extracted, the gas is returned\nto the mains and burned by Port Worth\nand other consumers in northern Texas.\nThe argon or helium plant was erected\nin great secrecy, a guard of soldiers\nbeing constantly maintained\naround it until after the armistice.\nDupring war days admission was denied\nto the public and only picked\nworkmen were employed.\nThe experiments- at the station had\nbeen so successful before the armistice\nthat it was predicted the use of the\nargon gas would speedily terminate the\nconflict. However, no opportunity was\never given of testing it in battle.\nThe gas is non-inflammable and noncombustible.\nIts value was discovered\nbefore the war, but the process of extracting\nit was then too costly to make\nthe gas practical. Government agents\nhave since perfected an economical\nmethod.\nThe gas is shipped from Fort Worth\nto Galveston and New Orleans in cylinders\nand loaded there aboard Navy Department\nvessels for transportation to\nballoon fields.\nBar Association Date.\nNEW ORLEANS.?The 1921 convention\nof the American Bar Association\nwill be held in Cincinnati on August\n80, September 1 and 2. This decision\nwas reached by the executive commit- I\ntee of the association, which held a\nthree-day session here.\nJoin Our Xm;\n\nfnv C?vi\nuvucijr ivi uavi\n\"Tke Depart\nnuuicn home. mo 3\n522 1\n4% KOfDAT 8ATDWS CLTTB r?\nnov open\nat 522 13thst.\nweekly;\nA Pep?It Ewrr Mtar l?\nJS for St weeks...\n39 for St g -T\nJ5 for St\nLit for St\nL2S for St i\n130 for St weeks\n135 for 50 weeks\nZOO for SO weeks\n5JO for 50 week?...^_\nSelect as but ss ?n nu r?n\ni*JS5S2Z*?\n?This Letter Spt\nTHE CATHOLIC UNIVE\nD?ir Friend*?I notice my\nNovember 39, ao I might u ml\nnow. Suppose we call it $7 per\ncard* you can punch me up an\nIt is rather curious, but in\nbeen sending this little saving t\nsome other saving I do?not em\nat (1 a dosen. etc^ and so on do\nall a man can do nowaday*. I 1\nfor each year the amount I recei\nFor instance, one year it paid f\nthe next it wired my bouse for eli\nit' anyhow; the next it painted i\nnever been spent foolishly. So, si\nsatisfaction.\nw\n-By BUD FISHER.\nM) FLEET HAS\nFAREWELL BY MR\nWeather Favorable on First\nDay of Cruise?Speed of\nTwelve Knots Made.\nBy Itadio to the Associated Press.\nU. S. S. NEW MEXICO. Pacific fleet.\nEn route South America. January S.?\nAn easy-rolling swell gently rocked\nthe battleships and destroyers of the\nPacific fleet on the first day of tHei*\ncruise to Panama and South America,\nwhere they will participate in\nmaneuvers with Atlantic fleet craft.\nPropitious weather greeted the fleer\nas it left San Diego and continued\nthroughout the day.\nThe battleships proceeded in column\nformation, screened by eighteen\ndestroyers of the squadron commanded\nby Capt. William V. Pratt, whose,\nflagship, the cruiser Birmingham,\nmaintained the advanced position of\nthe fleet during the day. A speed of\ntwelve knots, the Navy's \"economical\npace.\" was ordered after the fleet was*\nat sea. i\nAs the fleet cleared San Diego, a\nnumber of seaplanes and one dirigible\nfrom the naval air station at Sai?\nDiego .fluttered and floated aloft, bidding\nfarewell to the vessels and taking\npictures of their departure.\nThe colliers, oil tankers and other\nsupply ships of the fleet are one dayahead,\nthe main body being composed\nonly of fighting vessels. Much\nsatisfaction was expressed today\namong officers and men over the reported\narrival of the Pacific fleet seaplane\nsquadron at Acapulco, Mexico,\none day ahead of schedule.\nGIVEN INTERIOR POST.\nBoston Han Appointed Private Secretary\nto Payne.\nAppointment of Isidore Shaffer of\nBoston, Mass., to be private secre\ntary to the Secretary of the interior\nwas announced yesterday by Secretary\nPayne.\nMr. Shaffer served as official shorthand\nreporter to Gov. Cox on board\nthe Cox private train during October,\n1920. Me was-born in East Boston,\nMass.. in 1900. He came to\nWashington in December, 1917. as\nstenographer for the Food Administration.\nOn January 1. 1918, he. was\nappointed private secretary tu tri\ngeneral counsel of the Railroad Administration\nand on August 15. 191!'.\nlie became private secretary to the\nchairman of the United States Shipping\nBoard. He then went to Oklahoma\nto engage in the oil business,\nind was reappointed confidential\nclerk to the Secretary of the Interior\npn Jnly 1. 1920.\nPAINTING I r\nPkoae Ua far GitiaUM,\nR. K. FERGUSON, Inc.\n1114 9tk St. Ph. If. 9141\nPaimtlag Diwiliat\nuuu\nwill hneak a Cold, Fever and _\nGrippe quicker than anything\nwe know, preventing pneumonia.\n===g t\nm Chib Now\nngs and Loans\nrental Bank?\nHUJUIlTiHU AVEB(JE\n3th Street\nrnui AND VACATION, 1IU\nCloses January 17, 19ZL,\nat New Heine, 17th II\nand Peana. Ave. II\niAVlWGS\njaaioiMW| i??w-f Wttt-\n1 1 i% 'jSt*\n8 8 T7. 8 nir\n2530 AS OAS\n3731 38 3838\n5838 M StN\n8238 132 8332\n7338 L35 7435\n8738 138 8938\n18838 138 18138\n25838 438 25438\nry?make the deposits rentelT.\nla need af foods, do aet has*\ntads ?'S hhHioii the tttemt\ntjt pold with regn*oxity.\naks for Itself\nRSHY OF AMERICA\ningtos, D. C, 14 1?4\nKbw Savings card is paid up\nU begin a new deal hero and\nreek* When yon get out sent\n1 send it.\nthe past several years I have\no yon each week.?apart from\nash. I know, bnt with ears\nvn and np the list, ifs about\nhave taken great satisfaction.\nrved has done some real good.\nor half a new heating plant;\nsctricity, a good ways towards\nny house, and so on and has\nnail as it is, I have that much\nC. B.\n\nr\nW I","height":"29464","width":"22732"}}
